First pereopod (Fig. 8 D) moderately stout, overreaching antennal scale by half length of dactylus; dactylus (Fig. 8 E) about 0.7 times as long as palm, terminating in 2 darkly pigmented corneous claws; fixed finger terminating in single corneous claw. Second pereopod (Fig. 8 F) overreaching antennal scale by about 0.7 length of carpus; dactylus terminating in 2 small corneous claws; carpus divided into 7 articles. Third to fifth pereopods moderately long and slender, similar in shape and subequal in length. Third pereopod (Fig. 8 G) overreaching antennal scale by full length of propodus; dactylus (Fig. 8 H) about 0.2 times as long as propodus, moderately stout (about 3.0 times longer than deep), terminating in acute, darkly pigmented unguis, armed with 6 darkly pigmented accessory spinules on flexor margin, distalmost accessory spinule subterminal, distinctly larger than others, making tip of dactylus appearing biunguiculate; carpus about 0.6 times as long as propodus; merus armed with 6 ventrolateral spines in distal half. Fourth pereopod (Fig.
8 I
) overreaching antennal scale by 0.7 length of propodus; merus with 4 ventrolateral spines. Fifth pereopod (Fig. 8 J) overreaching distal margin of antennal scale by 0.3 length of propodus; merus with 1 spine at ventrolateral distal angle.
